  "name": "1 Corinthians 6:1–11",
  "localizedName": "1 Corinthians 6:1–11",
  "content": [
    {
      "tiptap": {
        "type": "doc",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "attrs": {},
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The Corinthian believers disagreed with one another a lot. They took each other to court. They trusted judges who weren’t believers to make wise decisions for them. Paul pointed out many problems with this."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "attrs": {},
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "He had already begged them to stop arguing. Here he begged them to deal with their problems in a godly way. They should never cheat others or do wrong to anyone. They should do good to everyone even to those who do wrong to them. They should seek help from wise believers for problems that they have with one another."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "attrs": {},
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Paul reminded the Corinthian believers that Jesus stopped the power of sin in their life. He made them "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108254",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "right with God"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". This means that they will be part of the kingdom of God. When God’s kingdom comes fully Jesus will share his authority with them."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "attrs": {},
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Jesus had told his "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108040",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "disciples"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " that they would judge the "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108286",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "12 tribes"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " of Israel (Matthew 19:28). Paul explained that believers would judge the entire world and even the "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108313",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "angels"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". That is the future that believers look forward to. So they should practice making wise judgements now."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
